## Bug Report Summary

I've completed a thorough exploration of the codebase and found the bug. Here are my findings:

### The Bug: Off-by-One Loop Error

**File:** `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775348231654-z7qkde/src/utils.ts`

**Full Source of `processItems` function:**
```typescript
export function processItems(items: string[]): string[] {
  const results: string[] = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++) {
    results.push(items[i].toUpperCase());
  }
  return results;
}
```

**Exact Line Causing the Bug:** Line 7
```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < items.length - 1; i++) {
```

**Root Cause:** The loop condition uses `i < items.length - 1` instead of `i < items.length`. This causes the loop to stop before processing the last item. For example:
- Array with 3 items (`["hello", "world", "foo"]`): loop runs for i=0 and i=1 only, skipping i=2 (the last item "foo")
- Array with 1 item: loop never executes, returning empty array instead of processing the single item

### Test Files

**File:** `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775348231654-z7qkde/tests/utils.test.ts`

**Full Contents:**
```typescript
import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { processItems, sum } from "../src/utils.js";

describe("processItems", () => {
  it("should process all items in the array", () => {
    expect(processItems(["hello", "world", "foo"])).toEqual([
      "HELLO",
      "WORLD",
      "FOO",
    ]);
  });

  it("should handle a single item", () => {
    expect(processItems(["test"])).toEqual(["TEST"]);
  });

  it("should handle two items", () => {
    expect(processItems(["a", "b"])).toEqual(["A", "B"]);
  });

  it("should return empty array for empty input", () => {
    expect(processItems([])).toEqual([]);
  });
});

describe("sum", () => {
  it("should sum numbers correctly", () => {
    expect(sum([1, 2, 3])).toBe(6);
  });

  it("should return 0 for empty array", () => {
    expect(sum([])).toBe(0);
  });
});
```

**Note:** The first test case ("should process all items in the array") will fail because it expects `["HELLO", "WORLD", "FOO"]` but the function returns only `["HELLO", "WORLD"]`. The test correctly identifies the bug!

